article.description: Looking a little rusty at times in their season opener, the Lady Raiders closed each half with a burst and beat Texas-San Antonio 76-48 Friday night in the opening round of the preseason women's NIT.
article.headline: Perkins picks up double-double
article.linkText: No. 10 Texas Tech puts away Texas-SA Friday night
article.story:
LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) -- Once No. 10 Texas Tech started moving
around a bit, the Lady Raiders were fine.

Looking a little rusty at times in their season opener, the Lady
Raiders closed each half with a burst and beat Texas-San Antonio
76-48 Friday night in the opening round of the preseason women's
NIT.

"Their team won the Southland Conference last year and they
came in here with nothing to lose," Tech coach Marsha Sharp said.
"I was pleased that we were able to generate some offense in
timely spots."

The most timely may have been at the end of the first half, when
Tech scored the final 11 points for a 32-20 lead. The Lady Raiders
closed the second half on a 16-2 run.

"I thought that as we went through it, we got a little better,
and I think we'll continue to see that happen," Sharp said.

Jia Perkins led Tech with 19 points, 13 rebounds and three
blocks. Alesha Robertson added 14 points for Tech, and Casey
Jackson and Jolee Ayers-Curry had 11 apiece.

"Obviously, they did a great job defensively, and we had a
little trouble getting into a groove," Ayers-Curry said. "We
missed some shots and got a little frustrated, but we had some
people make some big plays to fix that."

Lacy Mingee led Texas-San Antonio with 17 points and 10
rebounds. Kim Reed finished with 13 points, including 3-of-4 on
3-pointers. She also had five assists.

"They had that first-half run and we got down 12 points," said
Reed. "That sort of put us in a little bit of a hole. We hung in
there and played. But maybe there was a little bit of fatigue that
got us at the end of the first half."

A baseline shot by Robertson gave Tech a 52-33 lead with 10:22
remaining, but the Roadrunners fought back. Texas-San Antonio
pulled to 60-46 with 5:38 mark but made only two free throws the
rest of the way.

The Lady Raiders led 21-20 with 5:39 remaining in the first half
before breaking away. Robertson had five free throws during the
run.
